"“Follow the system that has to let us out,” Julie replied.\n\nThey moved up the ramp.\n\nThe service corridor was pressurized against smoke. Clean air pushed past them toward the lower tier, but the first breaths did not feel clean. Julie’s hands weakened around the case. Elias struck the wall with one shoulder and corrected without stopping. Marcus’s rib injury turned every inhalation into a measured choice.\n\nAt the first landing, a fire map showed the route.\n\nPRODUCTION EGRESS\n MECHANICAL BAY TWO\n LOADING DOCK THREE\n SOUTH SERVICE PERIMETER\n\nA red security door blocked the straight path. Its badge reader showed ACCESS SUSPENDED.\n\nThe crash bar beneath it glowed green.\n\nJulie hit it with her left forearm. The door released mechanically.\n\nOn the other side, the lower mechanical level had entered full evacuation. Exhaust fans started and stopped in different zones. Fire dampers moved inside the walls with hard metallic impacts. Condensation shook from overhead pipes onto the floor, making the painted walkways slick.\n\nTwo facilities technicians in gray coveralls came out of a chiller bay carrying emergency respirators. One saw the blood in Marcus’s hair and pointed toward the ramp behind them.\n\n“South dock is the fire exit. Move.”\n\n“We are,” Julie said.\n\nThe technician’s eyes dropped to the aluminum case. Before suspicion became a question, a radio on his shoulder called for all mechanical personnel to clear the lower tier. He turned away to answer it.\n\nJulie kept moving.\n\nA camera above the next junction rotated and centered on her face.\n\nShe did not look away. Apex already had her image. Hiding it now would cost time without changing the record.\n\nMarcus touched her shoulder. “Parallel corridor.”\n\nThrough a wired-glass panel on the left, dark uniforms moved at the same pace behind a fire partition. Mercer’s team had found the alternate route. They remained one wall away, matching the trio toward the loading level.\n\n“Door ahead,” Marcus said.\n\nA motorized smoke barrier began closing across their corridor.\n\nThe gap beneath it was still five feet.\n\nElias tried to run. His injured hip shortened the stride into a lurch.\n\nJulie reached the barrier first and pushed the case under. It slid across the wet floor and struck the wall beyond. She dropped to one knee and followed, protecting her right wrist against her chest.\n\nElias went next.\n\nMarcus arrived as the gap fell below three feet. His damaged heel caught the raised sill. He hit both hands on the floor and stopped beneath the moving steel.\n\nJulie seized the back of his coveralls with her left hand. Elias caught his sleeve.\n\nThey pulled him through as the safety edge brushed his shoulder and reversed long enough to clear the obstruction.\n\nThe barrier descended behind his boots.\n\nMarcus remained on his hands and knees.\n\n“Ribs?” Julie asked.\n\n“Still attached.”\n\n“That wasn’t useful the first time.”\n\n“It’s what I have.”\n\nShe got one arm beneath his left shoulder. Elias took the other side. Marcus stood between them, heavier than either could manage alone and unwilling to make them carry all of him.\n\nA wall clock above the mechanical-bay doors showed 05:06:41.\n\nThe loading level lay one ramp above.\n\nBehind the wired glass, Mercer’s team stopped at a closed fire barrier and split without hesitation. Two reversed toward the cross-passage. The others continued for another intercept.\n\n“They’re going around,” Marcus said.\n\n“We only need one route they don’t reach first.”\n\nThe ramp opened into a broad service bay lined with pumps, electrical switchgear, and parked maintenance carts. Building Three’s full alarm was louder here. Employees moved toward the south dock in small groups, badges visible, coats pulled over work clothes. No one knew which emergency to obey. Some looked toward the lower tier. Others followed the white strobes toward daylight.\n\nA campus emergency coordinator stood at the junction waving people toward the dock.\n\n“Out through South Service. Do not stop for vehicles or personal property.”\n\nJulie angled the case so her body hid most of it. Marcus kept his bloody side away from the coordinator. Elias lowered his head and moved with the evacuees.\n\nFor twenty yards, they were three injured people leaving a fire.\n\nThen the coordinator’s radio spoke Julie’s name.\n\nHe looked up.\n\nMarcus caught the change first. “Right.”\n\nThey broke from the evacuation line into Loading Dock Three.\n\nThe dock doors were open in emergency position. Predawn air moved through the bay, wet and cold. Beyond the concrete apron, service roads curved between utility buildings and the southern fence. White fire strobes reflected from puddles left by the night rain.\n\nA row of contractor vehicles stood along the dock wall: two utility pickups, a refrigeration truck, and a white maintenance van marked POTOMAC CRITICAL FACILITIES. The van faced the open service lane. Its rear doors were shut. A temporary Apex access placard remained fixed inside the windshield.\n\nA red cabinet beside the dispatch board displayed:\n\nEMERGENCY VEHICLE RELOCATION KEYS\n MAGNETIC LOCK RELEASED ON FIRE ALARM\n\nJulie opened it.\n\nEach key hung beneath a vehicle number and contractor name. She took the one tagged PCF-27.\n\nMarcus looked at the van. “Leg won’t work the pedals.”\n\n“I’m driving.”\n\n“Your wrist?”\n\n“Steering wheel is larger than a gate latch.”\n\nA security door opened at the far end of the dock.\n\nMercer’s second team entered in controlled formation, six people spread around parked equipment rather than clustered in the doorway. No one fired across the evacuating workers.\n\n“Vehicle,” Julie said.\n\nElias opened the side door. Marcus lifted the aluminum case with both forearms and pushed it into the cargo bay. The effort drew a sound from him that he tried to turn into a cough.\n\nJulie caught the case before it slid and wedged it behind the passenger seat. Its small display remained green.\n\nCAPTURE SEALED\n LOCAL MEDIA INTACT\n\nElias climbed in beside it.\n\nMarcus took the front passenger seat, using the door frame to lower himself without bending his ribs. Julie slid behind the wheel and started the engine.\n\nThe dashboard came alive with a contractor fleet screen.\n\nAPEX CAMPUS TELEMATICS ACTIVE\n VEHICLE PCF-27\n SOUTH SERVICE ROUTE AUTHORIZED\n\n“Tracked,” Marcus said.\n\nElias leaned forward from the cargo bay. “The module is behind the passenger kick panel. Apex requires the same installation on every contractor vehicle with lower-tier access.”\n\nMarcus looked down at his right leg. “Of course they do.”\n\n“Can you remove it?” Julie asked.\n\n“I can identify it. Someone else has to pull the panel.”\n\nMarcus hooked his fingers beneath the plastic trim. The first pull did nothing. He braced his good boot against the floor and tore the panel free with both hands.\n\nA black module the size of a deck of cards sat above the fuse block, secured by a steel clip and one locking connector.\n\nThe first containment operator reached the dock lane and raised a less-lethal launcher.\n\nJulie put the van in gear.\n\nA foam baton struck the rear door with a flat metallic blow.\n\nShe drove through the open dock entrance.\n\nThe service apron curved right toward the south utility gate. Evacuating contractor vehicles moved in the same direction ahead of them, guided by flashing arrows. Behind, the containment team spread into two security vehicles rather than chasing on foot.\n\n“Connector has a center tab,” Elias said. He had climbed between the seats and was bent over the open passenger footwell. “Gray lock first. Then black release.”\n\nHis cut finger slipped off the gray tab.\n\nMarcus reached down but could not fold far enough without his ribs stopping him.\n\n“Tool,” Elias said.\n\nJulie opened the small dashboard compartment with her left hand while steering with her right forearm. A tire gauge, registration sleeve, and flat service screwdriver slid onto the console.\n\nMarcus passed the screwdriver back.\n\nElias used its tip to lift the gray lock. His hands were still shaking. The module’s status light blinked green every two seconds, transmitting their location through the campus fleet network.\n\n“Not yet,” Julie said.\n\nElias looked up. “What?”\n\n“Wait until we know the gate mode. If the placard and transponder are opening the service perimeter, killing it here may stop us inside.”\n\nHe withdrew the screwdriver but kept one hand on the connector.\n\nThe fleet screen flashed.\n\nSECURITY BULLETIN — PRIORITY\n\nA photograph appeared from Julie’s temporary consultant record.\n\nJULIE M. O’DONNELL\n ARMED INSIDER THREAT\n SUSPECTED SABOTAGE OF NATIONAL-SECURITY INFRASTRUCTURE\n\nBelow it:\n\nSUBJECT BELIEVED TO HAVE INITIATED MALICIOUS ARGUS SOURCE CORRUPTION AND DELIBERATE FIRE IN BUILDING THREE.\n\nMARCUS L. REED — ARMED ACCOMPLICE\n ELIAS M. THORNE — POSSIBLE HOSTAGE\n RECOVER STOLEN ALUMINUM TELEMETRY CASE\n\nElias stared at the word HOSTAGE.\n\nThe black audit cartridge pressed a square outline against his shirt beside the circuit board that proved he had authenticated every choice himself.\n\n“They made me the victim,” he said.\n\n“For now,” Marcus replied. “Later they’ll use the same record to call you the attacker.”\n\nJulie kept her eyes on the service road.\n\nSix years earlier, the machine had been wrong and the surviving timeline had made her late. This time she had stopped the weapon, preserved the source record, and carried the evidence out in a government case.\n\nThe first official account said she had put the lie into Argus herself.\n\nAhead, the south utility gate stood open beneath white emergency lights. Its inbound lane was reserved for fire response. The outbound barrier remained raised while two contractor pickups cleared the campus. A security officer at the booth was lowering a manual swing arm across the lane beyond them.\n\n“Gate is closing,” Marcus said.\n\nThe first pickup passed.\n\nThe second accelerated through as the swing arm began moving.\n\nJulie pressed the accelerator.\n\nHer right wrist objected when the service road bent left. She trapped the steering wheel between her forearm and palm, pulled with her left hand, and kept the van inside the narrow lane.\n\nA county engine entered the separated inbound fire lane, lights reflecting across the wet pavement. Campus security could not block that lane. They could block Julie’s.\n\nThe officer at the booth saw the fleet bulletin on his terminal and stepped into the outbound lane with one hand raised.\n\nMarcus lowered his window.\n\n“Clear the fire route!” he shouted with the authority of a man who still sounded like a colonel even while bleeding through borrowed coveralls.\n\nThe officer hesitated long enough to look at the smoke alarms flashing across Building Three.\n\nJulie did not wait for him to decide.\n\nThe swing arm had crossed three quarters of the lane. She steered toward its flexible outer section and struck it at little more than walking speed.\n\nThe arm folded against the windshield pillar, scraped along the roof, and snapped free of its pivot. The officer jumped back.\n\nThe van cleared the gate at 05:14:36.\n\nBehind them, a security vehicle reached the utility road. Outbound contractor traffic and the broken swing arm stopped it short of the lane.\n\n“Now,” Julie said.\n\nElias drove the screwdriver beneath the black release and pulled.\n\nThe locking connector came free.\n\nThe fleet module’s green light died. The dashboard reported FLEET COMMUNICATIONS FAULT, then the contractor route map vanished.\n\nA service radio mounted beneath the dash remained alive, still switched to the county fire-interoperability channel. A dispatcher’s voice broke through the fire traffic.\n\n“All units, intelligence bulletin follows. Primary subject Julie O’Donnell, former Army intelligence officer, considered armed. Suspected deliberate sabotage at Apex Building Three and theft of classified national-security material. Associated white contractor van, Virginia commercial registration—”\n\nMarcus reached for the radio control, then stopped.\n\nTurning it off would not stop the bulletin. It would only make them deaf to it.\n\nThe utility road carried them away from the campus into the wet pre-dawn darkness. Building Three’s strobes receded in the mirrors. The aluminum case remained wedged behind Julie’s seat. Elias held the signed recovery cartridge against his chest. Marcus watched the security vehicle clear the gate behind them.\n\n“They have the plate,” he said. “Every camera from the dock to the fence. Pursuit will be on us as soon as they clear the fire lane.”\n\nJulie guided the van onto the first public road with her left hand fixed at the top of the wheel.\n\nNo one asked where they were going yet.\n\nElias pulled the dead transponder module from its clip and held it in his shaking hand while the radio repeated Julie’s name.\n\n---\n\n# Chapter 10 - The Capital Connection\n\nNorthern Virginia\n05:15 Eastern Daylight Time\n\nThe dispatcher repeated the van’s Virginia registration before Julie reached the second intersection.\n\nRainwater shone across the road in long black bands. Each time the tires crossed one, the steering wheel tugged against her injured wrist. She kept her left hand high on the rim and used her right forearm only when the van tried to wander toward the shoulder.\n\nThe fleet screen had gone dark except for the fault message Elias had created by pulling the telematics connector.\n\nFLEET COMMUNICATIONS FAULT\nVEHICLE PCF-27\n\nThe failure changed nothing about the white paint, the Potomac Critical Facilities markings, or the temporary Apex placard still fixed inside the windshield.\n\nBehind them, the service radio continued in a voice built to make alarm sound routine.\n\n“Primary subject Julie M. O’Donnell. Former Army intelligence officer. Considered armed. Suspected deliberate sabotage of national-security infrastructure and theft of classified material. Associated vehicle is a white Potomac Critical Facilities maintenance van, fleet identifier PCF-two-seven—”\n\nElias sat sideways in the cargo opening behind the seats. The dead transponder module lay in his left palm. His other hand pressed the signed recovery cartridge and the administrator-token circuit board against his chest beneath the open edge of his coveralls.\n\nThe radio gave Marcus’s name next.\n\nArmed accomplice.\n\nThen Elias’s.\n\nPossible hostage.\n\nHe looked down at the dead module as if it had made the accusation.\n\nMarcus watched the side mirror. Blood had dried from the cut above his right ear into the collar of his coveralls. He sat turned toward the window because facing forward forced his bruised ribs against the seat belt. His damaged boot rested flat and useless on the floor.\n\n“Security vehicle is through,” he said.\n\nJulie checked the rearview mirror.\n\nA pair of headlights had cleared the last rise behind them. Too high for a sedan. No visible emergency lights, but the spacing and speed matched the dark Apex unit that had been trapped at the broken gate.\n\n“How far?”\n\n“Two intersections. Maybe less if the light changes for them.”\n\nJulie held forty-five miles an hour.\n\nMarcus looked at her. “That’s the right speed.”\n\n“I know.”\n\n“A chase gives every camera a reason to remember us.”\n\n“I know that too.”\n\nThe next traffic signal changed to yellow while they were still a hundred yards away. Julie let the van slow.\n\nElias leaned forward. “You’re stopping?”\n\n“The plate is already known,” she said. “Running a red adds witnesses.”\n\nThe van stopped beneath a wet signal arm. A camera housing faced the intersection from the opposite mast. Julie could not tell whether it was recording traffic flow, reading plates, or doing nothing.\n\nShe assumed the first two.\n\nMarcus studied the cross street. “Left when it changes.”\n\n“Where?”\n\n“Old technical-support cutout. Fairfax County.”\n\n“Active?”\n\n“No.”\n\n“Erased?”\n\n“No.”\n\nJulie watched the signal remain red. “Connected to you?”\n\n“I used it twice. Eight years ago. The active inventory number was retired when the lease program consolidated.”\n\n“Archived records?”\n\n“Almost certainly.”\n\n“So it buys time.”\n\n“That’s all it ever did.”\n\nThe headlights behind them appeared at the far intersection.\n\nTheir light turned green.\n\nJulie went left.\n\nThe road narrowed between data-center compounds and unfinished office buildings. Ahead, three white contractor vans pulled out of a fenced construction site together, followed by a flatbed carrying cable spools.\n\nMarcus pointed. “Stay behind the flatbed.”\n\nJulie let the early-shift traffic gather around them until PCF-27 became one white work van among several.\n\n“Placard,” she said.\n\nElias set the transponder beside the aluminum case. He reached for the windshield with his left hand, missed the edge of the temporary Apex pass, and tried again. The adhesive resisted. The placard tore diagonally, leaving a clear corner stuck to the glass.\n\n“Good enough?”\n\n“No.”\n\nMarcus leaned across the console. The movement stopped his breathing for a second. He caught the remaining corner, peeled it free, and dropped both pieces beneath the seat.\n\n“Now it’s a known van without an Apex placard,” he said.\n\nThe radio crackled.\n\n“All county units, lookout request expanding from private security incident. Vehicle last observed departing south service perimeter. Do not approach without coordination. Classified material may be present.”\n\nNo sirens followed.\n\nThat made the response more dangerous. Patrol cars, traffic systems, and ordinary people could begin looking without warning them that the search had reached the next road.\n\nThe flatbed turned toward the parkway. Marcus directed Julie onto a service road beneath the transmission lines, behind a water-pumping station and a row of warehouse units whose loading docks faced away from the main road.\n\n“Camera coverage?” Julie asked.\n\n“Private. Uneven. I haven’t been here in years.”\n\n“So assume all of it.”\n\n“Yes.”\n\nThe Apex vehicle did not appear at the turn. Julie did not treat the empty mirror as success. The driver could have stayed on the parkway, moved ahead, or lost them in the contractor traffic and begun feeding the plate to systems they could not see.\n\nMarcus gave directions in short pieces. Right at the dead warehouse sign. Left beyond the electrical substation. Straight through a light-industrial park where the streetlights still burned against the wet dark.\n\nAt 05:31, a local news bulletin interrupted the fire traffic.\n\nApex Building Three had experienced what the announcer called a verified fire and a classified security event. One former Army officer and two male associates were being sought. The public was instructed not to interfere. Julie’s age and description came before her name.\n\nElias listened until the announcer repeated that he might be held against his will.\n\n“Turn it off.”\n\nMarcus’s hand moved toward the control, then stopped. “We need it.”\n\n“They’re talking about me.”\n\n“They’re also telling us what response is forming.”\n\nElias looked at Julie’s profile. “You don’t care what they call me as long as the radio is useful.”\n\nJulie kept her eyes on the road. “I care. I also need to know where the roadblocks will be.”\n\n“There aren’t any yet.”\n\n“Not yet.”\n\nThe service road ended at a broad commercial street. Julie waited behind a sanitation truck while cross traffic moved through the intersection. A marked county cruiser passed two lanes away without lights or siren.\n\nNo one in the van moved.\n\nThe cruiser continued north.\n\nMarcus watched it disappear. “Could have read us. Could have been looking somewhere else.”\n\n“Useful distinction,” Elias said.\n\n“It will be in five minutes.”\n\nJulie followed the sanitation truck through the light, then turned into an older industrial row with low brick fronts and steel service bays facing an alley. Marcus pointed toward a narrow driveway between two buildings.\n\n“Second bay from the end.”\n\nThe door was a corrugated roll-up panel painted the same gray as the wall. No government marking remained. A small lockbox sat behind a rain hood beside the frame.\n\nJulie stopped short of the driveway. “Can you open it?”\n\n“If the code hasn’t changed.”\n\n“And if it has?”\n\n“We keep moving.”\n\nThe radio repeated the registration.\n\nJulie turned in.\n\nMarcus got out slowly. His right leg nearly folded when the damaged heel touched pavement. He caught the mirror housing, waited, then limped to the lockbox. Rain darkened the blood already dried into his collar.\n\nHe entered five numbers.\n\nNothing happened.\n\nJulie watched the alley entrance in the mirror.\n\nMarcus cleared the keypad and entered six.\n\nThe lockbox opened.\n\nInside hung a brass key attached to an unlabeled steel tag. He unlocked the pedestrian door beside the bay, disappeared inside, and returned pulling a manual chain. The roll-up door rose with a dry rattle loud enough to carry down the block.\n\nJulie drove the van into darkness.\n\nMarcus lowered the door by hand.\n\nThe final strip of pre-dawn light disappeared across the concrete floor.\n\nPCF-27 was out of public view.\n\nIts known plate, warm engine, tire tracks, and route into Fairfax County still existed.\n\nDecommissioned Communications Cutout\n Fairfax County, Virginia\n 05:42 Eastern Daylight Time\n\nThe cutout smelled of dust, cold metal, and insulation that had absorbed ten years of summer heat.\n\nThe garage held an empty equipment rack, a stack of acoustic panels, and a workbench scarred by soldering irons. A narrow door led into the main room. Marcus found the breaker panel by touch and brought up two rows of fluorescent lights. One flickered without settling. The other cast a weak blue-white strip over obsolete radio consoles and cabinets with their inventory labels scraped away.\n\nA battery-backed clock showed 05:42:19.\n\nJulie carried the aluminum case through first.\n\nThe main room was smaller than the motel room where she and Marcus had inspected the original partial capture, though this one had been built for equipment rather than sleep. Old acoustic tile covered one wall. A disconnected regional map hung opposite it beneath dust. An analog scanner occupied the top of a rack beside a secure telephone with its handset wrapped in yellow decommissioning tape.\n\nA kitchenette opened off the rear wall. Beyond it were a washroom and a narrow observation room with opaque glass facing the alley. A steel fire door offered a second exterior exit.\n\nMarcus pointed from the garage threshold. “Workstation is in the observation room. Medical cabinet under the sink. Storage cabinet beside the rack.”\n\nJulie set the case on the equipment table and reached for the latches.\n\nBehind her, Marcus struck the door frame with one shoulder.\n\nThe sound was soft. The collapse was not.\n\nHis right leg gave way. He caught the jamb, but the movement pulled across his ribs. He lowered himself too quickly and ended sitting on the concrete with one hand pressed beneath his left arm.\n\nJulie left the case closed.\n\nShe crossed to him and crouched.\n\n“Look at me.”\n\n“I know who you are.”\n\n“That wasn’t the test.”\n\nShe switched on a flashlight from the first-aid cabinet. One pupil constricted, then the other. Equal. He tracked the beam without losing it.\n\n“Name.”\n\n“Marcus Reed.”\n\n“Location.”\n\n“An abandoned room you’re going to complain about later.”\n\n“Date.”\n\nHe gave it correctly.\n\n“Nausea?”\n\n“No.”\n\n“Double vision?”\n\n“No.”\n\n“Loss of consciousness?”\n\n“Not that I noticed.”\n\n“That answer is useless.”\n\n“It’s still no.”\n\nThe scalp cut above his right ear was short but dirty, the skin separated where the helmet rim had caught him at the gate. Blood had matted the hair around it. Julie felt no soft depression beneath her fingers, but she did not pretend that cleared him.\n\nThe cabinet contained sealed gauze, antiseptic, elastic wraps, two chemical cold packs, adhesive tape, and trauma shears with rust beginning at the hinge. The expiration dates ranged from three years old to eight.\n\n“Elias. Water.”\n\nHe stood too fast. The room shifted under him, and he caught the table with his left hand.\n\nJulie looked over. “Sit down.”\n\n“I can get water.”\n\n“You can get it after the floor stops moving.”\n\n“I’m not—”\n\n“You just missed the chair.”\n\n"